## The Oldest City in Skyrim

**Windhelm** claims the title of oldest human city in Skyrim — and potentially in all of Tamriel. Founded by **Ysgramor** himself after his conquest of the continent, the city stands on the banks of the **White River** in the Eastmarch hold, in the northeast of the province. Its massive walls, stone avenues, and imposing architecture testify to four thousand years of unbroken history.

The city was built as a monument to the glory of nascent Nordic civilization — an assertion of human dominance over a land once ruled by the Snow Elves. Every stone of its walls was laid with the awareness that one was building not merely a city, but the cradle of a civilization.

## The Foundation by Ysgramor

According to the **Songs of the Return**, **Ysgramor** founded Windhelm after completing his campaign of conquest against the Snow Elves who had massacred the colony of **Saarthal**. The heroic leader chose the site for both strategic reasons — control of the White River and access to the sea — and symbolic ones: the location roughly marked where his ships had landed on returning from Atmora.

The construction of the **Palace of the Kings** is said to have lasted the entirety of Ysgramor's life and that of his sons. Legend holds that the Thu'um was used to cut stone and assemble blocks, making the palace as much a work of the Voice as of human labor. Ysgramor himself died of old age there, and his tomb — located on an offshore island — became a sacred place of pilgrimage.

## The Palace of the Kings

The **Palace of the Kings** is the oldest and most revered building in Windhelm. Its great hall, with its stone throne and walls adorned with dragon skulls and war banners, embodies raw Nordic power. The palace served as the residence of Skyrim's High Kings for centuries, before the capital was transferred to **Solitude**.

The palace's architecture is characteristic of the ancient Nordic style: massive, functional, and imposing. Its grey stone walls are so thick they withstand the icy blasts of Eastmarch, and its towers dominate the urban landscape, visible for leagues in every direction. **Ysgramor's Throne** itself is carved from a single block of stone — an engineering feat for its time.

## The Early Eras

During the First Era, Windhelm served as the capital of a unified Skyrim under its first High Kings. The city prospered through maritime trade — its position on the White River, navigable to the sea, made it a major river port — and its status as a political and cultural center.

The **Grey Quarter** did not yet exist at this time; the city was exclusively Nordic. Relations with other races were defined by war rather than cohabitation. The Snow Elves had been exterminated or driven underground, and contacts with other elvish races remained limited and often hostile.

## The City's Architecture

The city is divided into several distinct districts whose layout reflects millennia of successive expansion. The **Stone Quarter** at the center forms the historic core, with its oldest buildings. The **Palace Quarter** surrounds the Palace of the Kings and houses noble residences. The outer walls, reinforced multiple times over the centuries, preserve visibly different layers of construction.

The famous **stone bridge** spanning the White River is one of the oldest works of engineering still in use in Tamriel. Its construction is attributed to the first successors of Ysgramor, and its longevity speaks to the excellence of early Nordic engineering.

## Political and Martial Center

Windhelm was for centuries the place where Skyrim's destinies were decided. The **Kingsmoot** — the assembly of Jarls to elect a new High King — was held there on many occasions. Tradition holds that only a ruler capable of holding Windhelm could claim the title of High King, making the city a political stake as much as a symbol.

The city also served as a muster base for great Nordic military expeditions. Armies marching south against Cyrodiil, east against Morrowind, or out to sea against Akaviri invaders frequently departed from Windhelm, whose forges and barracks could equip thousands of warriors.

## Trade and Prosperity

Despite its harsh climate, Windhelm prospered thanks to its strategic commercial position. The river port allowed the export of northern Skyrim's riches — furs, precious metals, timber — to southern markets. In return, goods from Cyrodiil and Morrowind traveled up the White River to feed the city's markets.

The mines of Eastmarch provided iron, steel, and gemstones, making Windhelm an important metallurgical center. Weapons and armor forged in its workshops were renowned throughout Skyrim for their durability, perpetuating the city's warrior tradition.

## A Legacy Across the Ages

Windhelm passed through four thousand years of history without ever losing its relevance. From the First Era — when it was the capital of a young Nordic kingdom — to the Fourth Era — when **Ulfric Stormcloak** made it the bastion of his rebellion against the Empire — the city remained a symbol of Nordic identity, resistance, and tradition. Its walls, which have seen hundreds of generations pass, continue to defy time and the storms of the north.
